description:
## Severity
Minor
## Dimension
concurrency
## Location
src/subagent.rs:1313-1331 (execute_task_tool background branch)
## Violation
The background-spawn branch executes:

```rust
if let Ok(handle) = Handle::try_current() {
    handle.spawn(async move {
        let result = run_subagent(&config_bg, &app_config_bg, &client_bg).await;
        if !result.success {
            BACKGROUND_AGENTS.fail(&agent_id_bg, result.output);
        }
    });
}
```

Three concurrency hazards:

1. If `Handle::try_current()` returns `Err`, the spawn is silently skipped. The caller has already been told an agent was started, but no tokio task exists. The agent will never finish, never produce a result, never error — the user waits forever on `agent_output`.
2. The spawned task's `JoinHandle` is dropped on the floor. There is no abort path (see issue #580 referenced in the source) and no way for the leader to know the task panicked: panics inside `handle.spawn` are silent absent a `.join()`.
3. The successful-completion path does NOT call `BACKGROUND_AGENTS.finish(...)` — finish is only called inside `run_subagent` keyed on the OTHER agent id (see #676 for the double-register bug). So even when the spawn completes successfully, the outer registration's `finished` flag is never flipped.

## Mandated refactor
- Bail with a user-visible error when `Handle::try_current()` fails — do not pretend the spawn worked.
- Store the `JoinHandle` inside the `BackgroundAgent` struct so it can be aborted and so panics surface via `JoinError`.
- After resolving the double-register bug (#676), make sure the outer `finish` path actually flips the registered agent's state on success.
## Filed from QA review dispatch
